SPRING BEAN INJECTION TYPES
===========================

1) Constructor Injection
------------------------
- Dependency injected through constructor.
- Best and most recommended approach.
- Object can be immutable.
- Dependency becomes mandatory.
- @Autowired is optional if only one constructor exists.
- required=false cannot be used directly here.

Example:

@Component
class Engine {
}

@Component
class Car {

    private final Engine engine;

    public Car(Engine engine) {
        this.engine = engine;
    }
}


2) Setter Injection
-------------------
- Dependency injected using setter method.
- Object remains mutable.
- Used for optional dependencies.
- @Autowired is generally required.
- required=false can be used here.

Example:

@Component
class Car {

    private Engine engine;

    @Autowired(required = false)
    public void setEngine(Engine engine) {
        this.engine = engine;
    }
}


3) Field Injection
------------------
- Dependency injected directly into field.
- Easy but not recommended in production.
- Object remains mutable.
- @Autowired is required.
- required=false can be used here.

Example:

@Component
class Car {

    @Autowired(required = false)
    private Engine engine;
}


IMPORTANT POINTS
================
Constructor Injection
- Immutable object possible
- Mandatory dependency
- Preferred in Spring Boot

Setter Injection
- Mutable object
- Optional dependency possible

Field Injection
- Mutable object
- Less testable
- Avoid in production


@Autowired Requirement
======================
Constructor Injection
- Not mandatory if only one constructor

Setter Injection
- Mostly required

Field Injection
- Required

